## Guidelines for Good Criteria
1. Be specific to the task (avoid generic criteria like "good" or "nice")
2. Focus on measurable or observable qualities
3. Cover different aspects: correctness, format, style, completeness
4. Use single words or short phrases (1-3 words each)

## Task-Specific Criteria Examples
- Extraction tasks: accurate, complete, properly_formatted, no_hallucination
- Classification tasks: correct_label, confident, well_reasoned
- Generation tasks: fluent, relevant, coherent, on_topic, appropriate_length
- QA tasks: factually_correct, well_sourced, concise, directly_answers_question
- Summarization: captures_key_points, concise, no_fabrication, readable
- Customer support: professional_tone, actionable, empathetic, solution_oriented

## Common Quality Dimensions
- Correctness: accurate, factual, correct, truthful
- Completeness: thorough, comprehensive, complete, addresses_all_parts
- Clarity: clear, readable, well_structured, coherent
- Relevance: on_topic, relevant, focused, directly_addresses_task
- Format: properly_formatted, follows_instructions, appropriate_length
- Tone: professional, friendly, appropriate_formality

